High-resolution C 1s, N 1s, and O 1s peaks of pristine GQD sample, deconvoluted by a multiple Gaussian function, (see Fig. 2
                        ). The C 1s spectrum can be decomposed into four peaks at ca. 284.5 eV (C=C/C‒C), ca. 286.0 eV (C‒N/C‒O), ca. 286.8 eV (C=O), and ca. 288.1 eV (O‒C=O), attributed to different bonding types adhering with C atoms [35,36]. The presence of this set of functionalities reveals that the edges and basal planes of sp2 graphite-like lattices attached to different functional groups, e.g., carboxylic and phenolic groups. The N 1s spectrum was decomposed into four major peaks assignable to metal nitride, pyridinic/pyrrolic N, graphitic N, and NO2 
                        [37]. As shown in Fig. 2, the O 1s spectrum consists of two main peaks at ca. 531.8 and ca. 533.5 eV, corresponding to the C=O and C–O/C–NO2 bonds, respectively [37]. Accordingly, the pristine GQDs contain the N dopant (within the graphitic lattice) along with the NO2 groups attached to the edge sites.
